card.desc: Pranic Initiation is a big step to take and when you decide to undergo such a ceremony it is important to be clear on your reason for initiating. The process involves long hours of starvation while your body undergoes something like "self-digestion".  Thus, you can consider the Pranic Initiation as a ceremony of death followed by reconstruction of the body through intellectual or spiritual stimulation. Your senses become more heightened as your organs break from metabolic action and as a consequence you transition into somewhat of a state of trance. Really, it is quite beautiful how introspective and aware you become. I find that I am more aroused by the intricacies of life and how to exist within it.

card.desc: Surprisingly, I do not prefer Dry Fasting! Goodness, it is challenging for me unless I begin during the wee hours of midnight when Yin is dominant. Really I prefer juice fasting and indulging in a raw diet from time to time. My roots are wedged into multiple Native American tribes and so when I participate in a dry fast I think of them. During these days, I purposefully embrace these facets of myself specifically because it is a practice that they have made sacred. Participating in Dry Fasting with my Pranic Family makes it all the more valuable, as it allows me to reenact those moments of vulnerability with a tribe.

cards.desc: Dry fasting offers a moment of contemplation of what we're putting our refuge. For those few days we only take in air as external sustenance. The healing, joy, and mental freedom is unmatched by other fasting practices. This is coming from someone who's done a 24 day water fast.

cards.desc: I’ve in some way all my life been on what can be called a spiritual path. I’ve been looking for answers for questions like, what am I doing here, what’s my purpose and how can we all live on the earth in love and peace; treating each other in the same way we would like to be treated ourselves. I have wanted to learn to live life more fully, without worry, stress and negative feelings. I didn’t understand why life had to be so hard instead of being full of enjoyment, happiness and love. Now I know that that’s exactly what we are capable of creating ourselves.
cards.name: How I got on the journey

cards.desc: I’ve gone through all kinds of food trying to find out what suited me the best. For a while I had a very sensitive stomach and did not tolerate any fruits, vegetables or fibers. But I was determined to become vegan because that’s what my heart told me to do. Now I have for some time had no problems eating fruits and vegetables. For the last few weeks I have eaten mostly fruits, made myself smoothies and drunk juices.
cards.name: What diet are you on?

cards.desc: I really enjoy the peace and calmness in my body that comes when I don’t eat or drink anything for at least one day. I also like to cleanse my body and give it some rest to repair and rejuvenate itself. Last but not least it’s part of my path to a pranic living lifestyle.
cards.name: Have you tried Dry Fasting?

cards.desc: What I really love from being a part of the pranic family is having a community of like minded people that support and help each other. It‘s so precious having a group of people to share your journey with and talk about what’s on your mind. What is even more important is the love, compassion and gratefulness that we share in this wonderful group.
cards.name: Have you done a Pranic Initiation?

cards.desc: Through the pranic initiation I realized that I’m capable of so much more than I would have thought I could do just a few months ago. I feel like I can go through anything because of the inner strength I’ve gained from the initiation. I found so much peace and joy, though the process was also very challenging at times. I now know from my own experience that I’m limitless and can live on everything that I put my intention and focus on, for example listening to beautiful music, walking in nature and being around loving and caring people.
cards.name: What is your motive?

cards.desc: I like to share both relaxing and strengthening yoga practices that I practice everyday, my favorite Chi Gong exercises, breathing exercises that have helped me a lot on my journey and also meditation and visualizing techniques that help people draw into their lives everything they want to.
cards.name: What daily practices you enjoy?

cards.desc: As a steward I see myself focusing on a minimalistic lifestyle because that’s something that has come very strongly to me since I started on my pranic path. I have gotten so much more unattached to everything in my life, both external things and internal like habitual thinking, emotions and behavior that has been part of my life uninterrupted until recently. Removing many of my material things has given me so much joy and helped me to see how very little we really need to live a happy life.
cards.name: My focus is on Simple Living

I am doing all of this just to find out there is nothing to find out about this kind- of -journey. To help realize this reality for what it is.

cards.desc: I was invited into the Pranic family by the lovely Kamila. I met Kamilla online and after exchanging some highlights from our lives, she encouraged me to join the Pranic family. I have been a member ever since! By definition, though, my Pranic journey began long before our introduction and I want to emphasize that being on such a journey means that you are extracting life-force through observation and introspection. You become cognosin of the forces of life and choose to transition within these natural laws, becomming sovereign, living within. It is a phenomenon that we have all experienced in one way or the other.
cards.name: How I got on the journey

cards.desc: Currently, I am on a plant-based diet. I transitioned into a plant-based diet at the age of 18, after making the decision to expound upon my knowledge of spirituality. In my education, I learned more about the energetical value of food and how it contributed to our psychological well-being. It was not long before I felt these dietary changes reflect positively within my spirituality and so eating holistically is something I prefer doing.
cards.name: What diet are you on?

cards.desc: Surprisingly, I do not prefer Dry Fasting! Goodness, it is challenging for me unless I begin during the wee hours of midnight when Yin is dominant. Really I prefer juice fasting and indulging in a raw diet from time to time. My roots are wedged into multiple Native American tribes and so when I participate in a dry fast I think of them. During these days, I purposefully embrace these facets of myself specifically because it is a practice that they have made sacred. Participating in Dry Fasting with my Pranic Family makes it all the more valuable, as it allows me to reenact those moments of vulnerability with a tribe.
cards.name: Have you tried Dry Fasting?

cards.desc: I enjoy the company and appreciate the multitude of minds that I get to interact with. Though we are like-minded everyone is so unique and offers a valuable perspective and that is something, I enjoy. I can find something within each of them, that I can resonate with and they are truly a gift.
cards.name: Have you done a Pranic Initiation?

cards.desc: Pranic Initiation is a big step to take and when you decide to undergo such a ceremony it is important to be clear on your reason for initiating. The process involves long hours of starvation while your body undergoes something like "self-digestion".  Thus, you can consider the Pranic Initiation as a ceremony of death followed by reconstruction of the body through intellectual or spiritual stimulation. Your senses become more heightened as your organs break from metabolic action and as a consequence you transition into somewhat of a state of trance. Really, it is quite beautiful how introspective and aware you become. I find that I am more aroused by the intricacies of life and how to exist within it.
cards.name: What is your motive?

cards.desc: I really love to read. I am an herbalist and study medicinal practices from all over the world including Traditional Chinese Medicine and Acupuncture. I dabble in Curanderismo and would really like to learn more from our Southern Natives. You will definitely hear me sharing these types of learnings, learnings about the body and how it works, and the philosophies often associated with different cultural perspectives.
cards.name: What daily practices you enjoy?
